${h3}0.42 - 2001/12/08:${h3end}

New features:${pul}

${bullet}CTRL-E instead of 'E' now forces invocation of the addressbook when
${indent}entering a message in a non-netmail, non-email area. This only gets you
${indent}the real name portion. I don't really see the use of this myself -- the
${indent}entire point of the addressbook is to store netmail and email addresses,
${indent}not simple names -- but it was requested, and easy to do, so here it is.
${indent}It works wherever 'E' works (area list, letter list, letter window),
${indent}although due to space considerations and laziness, it only appears in the
${indent}letter list's help menu. Note that you can still only use the 'L' function
${indent}of the addressbook on messages where an address is present. (Changing that
${indent}would be more involved.) Suggested by Greg Sears.
${ulend}
Bug fixes and such:${pul}

${bullet}In the Win32 version, under Windows XP and perhaps 2000 (?), the window
${indent}was scrolled up on returning from a shell (unarchiving, etc.), unless the
${indent}scrollback buffer was disabled. Although cosmetic, this was enough of a
${indent}nuisance that I'm releasing 0.42 now.

${bullet}Added strings.h to the includes in mmail.h to get it to compile under QNX.
${indent}(If you're trying this, edit the Makefile to say \"-lncurses\" rather than
${indent}\"-lcurses\".) Note that the background characters (ACS_BOARD and
${indent}ACS_CKBOARD) aren't what they should be in QNX; otherwise, it works well.

${bullet}New error message for the case when no files are found in the work
${indent}directory after uncompression, but no error code was returned by the
${indent}unarchiver. (Previously this resulted in the misleading message \"Packet
${indent}type not recognized\"; that message is now reserved for times when there
${indent}are actually some files in the work directory.)

${bullet}Since version 0.38, when I moved development to a new computer, the
${indent}documentation file \"mm.txt\", included with the DOSish ports, had not been
${indent}converted correctly by the script that builds those archives -- it was
${indent}left as raw troff code instead of a rendered man page, and the line
${indent}endings were left as LF (Unix style). In other words, it was basically
${indent}illegible. The discouraging part of this is that no one reported it, which
${indent}makes me think that no one's reading the documentation. :-(

${bullet}Other, minor updates to the documentation.
${ulend}
${h3}0.41 - 2001/10/16:${h3end}

New features:${pul}

${bullet}Options can now be specified on the command line. Any .mmailrc option may
${indent}be used, though not all will actually work (some of them are used in
${indent}initialization before this point). Options are preceded by '-' or \"--\",
${indent}and must finish before a packet is specified. See the man page for more
${indent}details.

${bullet}New keyword: \"IgnoreNDX\". This makes MultiMail ignore the *.NDX files in
${indent}QWK packets, in favor of the new (slower, but safer) indexing method that
${indent}uses only MESSAGES.DAT. Turn this on if you get bogus *.NDX files from
${indent}your BBS (as seems all too common).
${ulend}
Bug fixes and such:${pul}

${bullet}Big bug: Reply splitting in QWK on DOSish systems (DOS, Win32, OS/2)
${indent}generated a corrupt reply packet (always). It's been this way a long time;
${indent}possibly since the message split feature was introduced. I never noticed
${indent}it because a) I rarely split messages, b) I seldom use QWK anymore -- all
${indent}SOUP and BW now, c) I never use the DOSish ports, except for testing, and
${indent}d) the split replies _look_ OK, until you close and reopen the packet. I
${indent}had a lot of bug reports which, in retrospect, seem to be about this, but
${indent}I never got enough detail to make sense of the problem, until Ken Hrynchuk
${indent}reported on it. Many thanks to him.

${bullet}Bogus values in the *.NDX files of a QWK packet are now checked for and
${indent}often handled without having to abort. In some cases, MultiMail is able to
${indent}revert to the alternate indexing method automatically; in others, the
${indent}message \"ERROR READING MESSAGES.DAT\" appears in the letter list, instead
${indent}of the gibberish that resulted when following a bogus pointer. For those
${indent}cases which still cause problems, see the new \"IgnoreNDX\" keyword.

${bullet}Problems with the ncurses configuration on Mandrake 8 (well, on my system,
${indent}anyway) caused MultiMail to hang on searches or ANSI animation. There's
${indent}now a partial workaround for this (searching works OK, ANSI anim still
${indent}hangs) in MultiMail. But the proper fix is this: Download the ncurses
${indent}source; configure; manually edit the line in curses.h that defines bool to
${indent}say \"typedef unsigned char bool\" instead of \"typedef unsigned bool\";
${indent}compile; and install. I still have to figure out why the typedef comes out
${indent}that way; the same version of ncurses (with the same configure script)
${indent}works correctly on my old Slackware system. You might see this problem on
${indent}other systems as well.

${bullet}Blue Wave messages with Internet kludge lines (as produced by version 4
${indent}doors) were causing segfaults. This is what happens when a feature doesn't
${indent}get exercised for a while. :-(

${bullet}Segfault on a message with a MSGID kludge line, but no other body text.

${bullet}In the Win32 port, packet time stamping now works under Win 9x, though it
${indent}still doesn't work on network shares under NT.

${bullet}Some unprintable characters weren't being filtered out when running in an
${indent}xterm, resulting in a garbled display.

${bullet}In the 16-bit port, in QWK packets with no *.NDX files, MultiMail was
${indent}failing if the MESSAGES.DAT file was larger than 32K.

${bullet}The END key now works under screen (for example) with ncurses.

${bullet}The message-splitting function now uses parentheses instead of brackets,
${indent}and the part number is padded with leading zeroes. I did this to match
${indent}standard practice in the alt.binaries.* newsgroups.

${bullet}Added the undocumented option \"-#\" to the default command lines for PKZip
${indent}and PKUnzip. This supresses output, equivalent to the \"-q\" option used in
${indent}the default InfoZip command lines. Suggested by K.H. (Note that if you're
${indent}upgrading, you'll have to put it in manually, if you want it; as always,
${indent}MultiMail won't alter values that are already specified in its config
${indent}file.)

${bullet}Shelled commands (zip, unzip, edit) can now handle paths with spaces in
${indent}them.

${bullet}On MultiMail's first run, on DOSish systems, the MMAIL.RC ended up with
${indent}paths that had a mix of slash and backslash characters. Although this
${indent}didn't interfere with operation, it was a cosmetic defect.

${bullet}The defaults in the top-level Makefile have changed to \"${lt}curses.h${gt}\" for
${indent}CURS_INC, and \"-lcurses\" for LIBS. Most/all distros of Linux, as well as
${indent}FreeBSD, have replaced the older curses with ncurses by now, and some
${indent}(e.g., Debian) lack the old-style compatibility links, so this now seems
${indent}to be the most widely compatible configuration. (The old defaults are now
${indent}in the first commented-out example section.)

${bullet}I figured out the problem that led to the hasty release of version 0.40 --
${indent}it was a missing pair of parentheses. ${lt}sigh${gt} Or to look at it another way,
${indent}a misunderstanding of operator precedence.
${ulend}
