${h3}0.39 - 2001/04/13:${h3end}

New features:${pul}

${bullet}Mouse functionality. Currently, this is only supported under X (with
${indent}either ncurses or PDCurses), in the Linux console with gpm, and in the
${indent}Win32 port. See the man page for a description of how to use this -- not
${indent}well-described there, but it should be fairly intuitive.

${bullet}A new flag to join Marked, Replied, Read and Private: Saved. It's set
${indent}automatically when a message is saved (natch). It appears in the letter
${indent}list as a lowercase 's', and as a new flag in the group displayed in the
${indent}letter window. (Note that if the message is also Marked, only the 'M' will
${indent}appear in the letter list -- I was short of columns.) Because of this, the
${indent}names displayed in the letter window have been shortened. Saving a message
${indent}no longer marks it as Read, since that seems redundant now (though it
${indent}still does clear the Marked flag). The new flag is mapped appropriately in
${indent}.XTI files, but not in MAIL.FDX, so it's not preserved in OPX packets.

${bullet}New transparency method: The transparent background color is the one
${indent}specified by \"Main_Back\" in the colors file, rather than always black.
${indent}This allows the use of transparency with light backgrounds, etc. (See the
${indent}screenshots web page.)
${ulend}
Bug fixes and such:${pul}

${bullet}A longstanding bug: It was impossible to rename packets after opening
${indent}them. Finally fixed, as part of a big string-operation cleanup.

${bullet}Another longstanding one, also part of the BSOC: On some platforms, when
${indent}specifying a packet name on the command line, names of certain lengths
${indent}wouldn't work. After I finally sorted this out, the surprising thing was
${indent}that it had ever been working for names of any length. ${lt}sigh${gt}

${bullet}Many potential buffer overflows and bogus limits fixed in the BSOC. Others
${indent}remain. :-(

${bullet}Since time immemorial: When pulled from the address book into a message,
${indent}the \"To:\" field was being restricted to 29 characters, regardless of packet
${indent}type. Also, the length of names in the address book had been limited to 44
${indent}characters.

${bullet}A fresh one: Reply packets were being stamped with a bogus date.

${bullet}The packet list, if sorted by time, is no longer rearranged when a packet
${indent}is Touched.

${bullet}Replies are now preserved in the event of a crash during the write-out
${indent}process. Inspired by Matt Munson.

${bullet}The highlight bar wasn't showing up in XCurses -- probably since about
${indent}version 0.18, which shows how often I try that port. (I also had some
${indent}other problems with XCurses, as yet unsolved; it sometimes locked up on
${indent}starting.)

${bullet}Stupid bug in SOUP: segfault on message areas with 8-character filenames.

${bullet}The line showing \"BBS:\" and \"Sysop name:\" in the area list is now omitted
${indent}if neither is defined (as in SOUP packets), leaving an extra line for the
${indent}areas themselves.

${bullet}The minimum screen size is now 60x17. I'm shooting for 40 columns. ;-)
${ulend}
${h3}0.38 - 2001/02/03:${h3end}

New features:${pul}

${bullet}First new version in over seven months! See, it's not dead after all.

${bullet}Transparency: There are three new keywords in the .mmailrc which are
${indent}mainly for making the background transparent, for use in programs like
${indent}Eterm which can put an image in the background: \"UseColors\" (default:
${indent}yes), \"Transparency\" (default: no), and \"BackFill\". \"Transparency\" only
${indent}works in ncurses; \"BackFill\" is the only one available on all platforms.
${indent}See the man page for more on these.

${bullet}New date/timestamp handling: When updating packets with the .red markers,
${indent}MultiMail now preserves the original timestamp of the file. This means
${indent}that date sorting will reflect the order in which packets arrived, rather
${indent}than the order in which they were last read. (Note, however, that this
${indent}feature doesn't quite work correctly in the Win32 port (see README.win).
${indent}One way around this would be to use PKZIP with the \"-k\" option; or just
${indent}use the DOS port.) Inspired by Ingo Brueckl. At first I had this toggled
${indent}by a keyword, but then...

${bullet}The complement to the new timestamp handling is the 'T' function in the
${indent}packet window, which \"Touches\" a file, setting its timestamp to the
${indent}current time. I needed this because I actually depend on the timestamps
${indent}being updated sometimes.

${bullet}New \"ExpertMode\" option supresses the help text, for those who are
${indent}familiar with the commands and would rather use more of the screen for
${indent}text. Four lines are gained in the packet, area and letter lists, among
${indent}other gains.

${bullet}In a related note, you now can gain seven lines in the packet list by
${indent}undefining VANITY_PLATE in config.h, but this is strictly a compile-time
${indent}option. :-)

${bullet}OPX secretly restored. ;-)
${ulend}
Bug fixes and such:${pul}

${bullet}Removed several older keywords to simplify the .mmailrc: BuildPersArea
${indent}(even on my XT, it didn't really take much longer), MakeOldFlags,
${indent}UseScrollBars, and AutoSaveRead (all these are now always on).

${bullet}The default editor for the Win32 port is now \"start /w notepad\". I'm not
${indent}crazy about this, but under NT (in VMware), EDIT was completely locking
${indent}up. Unfortunately MS provides no text-mode, native Win32 editor. (BTW, an
${indent}interesting aside: Under NT, \"notepad\" is actually sufficient (the calling
${indent}program waits for it to return); the \"start /w\" bit is for the benefit of
${indent}9x, which otherwise launches notepad and returns immediately.)

${bullet}The Win32 port had trouble with the most recent Win32 version of PDCurses,
${indent}because it now returns shift, alt and control immediately as keystrokes.
${indent}(XCurses presumably had the same problem, but I didn't test this.) This is
${indent}worked around now.

${bullet}SOUP (and BW v4): Newsgroup lines which exceed the width of the display
${indent}now end in \"...\" to indicate a continuation. (You can see the entire
${indent}\"Newsgroups:\" line by pressing 'X' for full headers.)

${bullet}SOUP (and BW v4?): Broken \"References:\" lines which contained no proper
${indent}message ID's were causing segfaults. Reported by Peter Karlsson. BTW,
${indent}would the perpetrators of these broken messages please fix them?

${bullet}SOUP: In 'm' mode, checking for \"From \"-line dividers is a little more
${indent}rigorous; the line must now also contain an '@'. This eliminated all the
${indent}false positives I was seeing on Pine-generated mail folders.

${bullet}In packets where the list of subscribed areas is not known (e.g., all
${indent}plain QWK and SOUP packets), the \"Subscribed\" mode in the area list is now
${indent}skipped automatically.

${bullet}The default color scheme is now a little less day-glo, :-) and shows up
${indent}better on some terminals. The old one is still available in tradit.col.
${indent}Let me know what you think.

${bullet}Ncurses' built-in SIGWINCH handler is on by default in 5.0+; this was
${indent}conflicting with MultiMail's handler. It should now work OK, but see
${indent}NCURSES_SIGWINCH in interfac.h if you're not using ncurses' defaults.

${bullet}When going backwards through messages via '-' and backing out of an area,
${indent}the display was not updated correctly. I've also changed the behavior of
${indent}'-' in this instance to go back to the last non-empty group instead of the
${indent}last group (more consistent with '+').
${ulend}
${h3}0.37 - 2000/06/28:${h3end}

New features:${pul}

${bullet}Moved web site and email from ClarkNet to SourceForge. Among other
${indent}benefits, this means that old versions of the MultiMail source code are
${indent}now archived online, going back to 0.1. Binaries (for certain platforms)
${indent}from 0.36 on will also be archived.

${bullet}New compression type: tar/gz. (New .mmailrc keywords: \"tarCompressCommand\"
${indent}and \"tarUncompressCommand\".) Unlike the other types, this recompresses the
${indent}entire packet when updating the .red flags, so it can be a bit slow. Also,
${indent}the supplied command lines assume GNU tar, which has gzip built-in.
${indent}Separated gunzip/tar and tar/gzip command lines would require a (simple)
${indent}external script. MultiMail only checks for the gzip signature. Requested
${indent}by Peter Karlsson for compatibility with GNUS.
${ulend}
Bug fixes and such:${pul}

${bullet}The packet list could crash on directory names longer than 32 characters.
${indent}Reported by Tuukka Lehtinen.

${bullet}Zero-length messages caused a segfault. Reported by T.L.

${bullet}In SOUP packets with index files, the .idx file would be opened instead of
${indent}the corresponding .msg file. Reported (indirectly) by Peter Karlsson.

${bullet}GNUS apparently uses a bogus identifier 'n' in the first position of the
${indent}attribute fields of the AREA files in the SOUP packets it generates,
${indent}equivalent to the standard type 'u'. MultiMail now recognizes this flag.
${indent}Reported by P.K.

${bullet}In MakeChain(), rejoin is now always applied to non-quoted lines. This
${indent}looks better in most cases; in particular, where space padding on the end
${indent}of a line resulted in a line of exactly 80 columns. (Previous versions of
${indent}MultiMail would print an extra blank line then.)

${bullet}relist() is now always called from MakeActive() in the area list and
${indent}little area list. This means that the list is updated properly in Active
${indent}mode, among other things.

${bullet}In the packet list search function, the wrong packet was highlighted.

${bullet}On some platforms (including the NetBSD m68k binary distributed on the web
${indent}site), forced word-alignment of structs broke the \"old-style\" (.PDQ-based)
${indent}offline config in Blue Wave mode. (Yes, I should've anticipated this after
${indent}the similar bug with OPX mode in 0.32.)

${bullet}The signature-adding routine will now skip CR characters, so (in
${indent}principle) a .sig could be shared between Unix and DOSish readers. Other
${indent}text files should still be kept separate. Inspired by Martin Prieto.

${bullet}The backslashes that had briefly appeared in the DOSish versions' packet
${indent}windows had reverted to forward slashes again in 0.36. :-)
${ulend}
${h3}0.36 - 2000/04/28:${h3end}

New features:${pul}

${bullet}The area list has a new mode, \"Active\", to accompany the existing \"All\"
${indent}and \"Subscribed\" views. The Active mode lists only those areas that
${indent}contain messages. The L key now cycles among all three modes. (Note that
${indent}in some cases, two modes may be equivalent; e.g., in plain QWK packets,
${indent}there's no way to distinguish Active from Subscribed.)

${bullet}There's also a new \"Marked\" view in the letter list. If any messages in
${indent}the area are marked, the L key cycles between all, unread, and marked
${indent}views. (Otherwise, it toggles all/unread, as before.) Marked messages are
${indent}no longer automatically included in the unread view.

${bullet}In the packet and letter lists, the current sort modes are now displayed.
${indent}And in the area and letter lists, the current mode is displayed. The
${indent}number of files is shown in the packet list, but only if the total number
${indent}of items (files + directories) exceeds the window length. The area and
${indent}letter lists now work similarly, showing the number of items only when
${indent}they exceed the window length.

${bullet}By popular demand, the default modes for the area list (all, subscribed,
${indent}or active) and the letter list (all or unread) can now be set in .mmailrc.
${indent}See the \"AreaMode\" and \"LetterMode\" keywords.

${bullet}Old-style Blue Wave offline config, using .PDQ files, is now supported.
${indent}(.UPI/.NET replies still aren't, yet.) Requested by Russell Tiedt.

${bullet}Specifying a directory on the command line now opens the packet window on
${indent}that directory. No more items are read from the command line afterwards.

${bullet}In Unix, the \"~\" character is now recognized as a synonym for the contents
${indent}of the \"HOME\" environment variable in input, and is also used that way in
${indent}the packet list display. (However, \"~username\" is not supported.)

${bullet}The Tab key works as an alternative to Enter in input windows.

${bullet}The BCC port is now the \"standard\" Win32 port. (The RSX/NT port is still
${indent}available, renamed mmrsxNNN.zip.)

${bullet}New BeOS binary.
${ulend}
Bug fixes and such:${pul}

${bullet}Makefile.tcc and Makefile.bcc are now sensible -- no more renaming or
${indent}moving kludges. :-) Also, the \"UNUSED_PARAMS\" nonsense is gone, and
${indent}MultiMail compiles without warnings under BCC.

${bullet}The message and ansi viewers can now handle ${gt} 64k in the 16-bit version,
${indent}depending on available memory.

${bullet}In myreaddir(), the DJGPP, Turbo and Borland ports (mmdos, mmxt, and
${indent}mmwin) now use findfirst()/findnext() instead of readdir()/stat(). This
${indent}means that the packet window opens significantly faster on large
${indent}directories. (stat() is fine in Unix, but slow in MS-DOS, where it's
${indent}implemented via findfirst().) Also, the list is now built in a single
${indent}pass, instead of one pass for files and another for directories, resulting
${indent}in a speedup on all platforms.

${bullet}Test of read-only status now works in Borland/Turbo ports.

${bullet}Grabbing of Fidonet addresses was broken in some situations, causing
${indent}segfaults. Reported by Greg Paski.

${bullet}When lines ended with spaces, they could be quoted incorrectly. Reported
${indent}by Jim Hanoian.

${bullet}Tab characters in messages could cause segfaults in some cases.

${bullet}Soft CR stripping wasn't working.

${bullet}Looking through my (very) old packets, I found some in which another
${indent}reader (?) had added its own files to a packet with the names \"a0000.ndx\"
${indent}and \"a0001.ndx\", which made MultiMail generate a bogus area 0 for those
${indent}packets. Fixed.

${bullet}The keypad mostly didn't work in the BCC (Win32) port of MultiMail.
${indent}Reported by Jeff Foy.

${bullet}Using the Goto function in the packet list now puts the highlight bar on
${indent}the first file, as when a directory is selected by pressing Enter. In Lynx
${indent}mode, going left (back) in the packet list now actually goes to the
${indent}previous directory, instead of the parent directory, and the previous
${indent}highlight position is restored.

${bullet}When cycling through sort modes in the letter list, sort by \"To:\" is now
${indent}skipped for areas which have no such field (i.e., Usenet areas).

${bullet}Wrapped header lines in SOUP are now displayed in the correct color.

${bullet}When writing out offline config (add/drop), the area list was scanned, but
${indent}the current area number was not preserved. This sometimes led to minor
${indent}cosmetic problems in the reply area. Reported by J.H.

${bullet}Finally replaced the ugly #define list in mmcolor.h with an enum.

${bullet}Some malformed Internet \"From:\" lines appear without a space between the
${indent}name and address. In such cases, MultiMail was stripping the last letter
${indent}of the real name.

${bullet}Several new error messages.

${bullet}The color files are now archived separately within the binary archives, to
${indent}reduce clutter. Now if I can just figure out how to combine some of the
${indent}documentation files in a sensible way...
${ulend}
