${bullet}The \"Replied\" flag is now set by O- and N-type replies, as well as R.

${bullet}Some code reorganization.${ulend}

${h3}0.15 - 1998/05/12:${h3end}

New feature:${pul}

${bullet}If you back out from a packet, to the packet list, you can now reselect
${indent}the same packet without it being decompressed again. Thanks to Robert
${indent}Vukovic for convincing me of the need for something like this.${ulend}

Bug fix:${pul}

${bullet}In DOS, the default editor (edit.com) didn't actually work, because it
${indent}didn't understand paths with slashes instead of backslashes. I missed this
${indent}because it worked with Qedit. :-) The slashes are now flipped on the
${indent}pathnames passed to external editors and archivers (in DOS only). Thanks
${indent}to kifox@geocities.com for reporting the problem.${ulend}

${h3}0.14 - 1998/04/25:${h3end}

Bug fix:${pul}

${bullet}A more subtle line-ending bug... under MSDOS, extra characters were
${indent}sometimes added to the end of a reply. (Unix versions were not
${indent}affected.)${ulend}

${h3}0.13 - 1998/04/24:${h3end}

Bug fix:${pul}

${bullet}While making changes to accomodate MSDOS line endings, I made a small
${indent}oversight that caused replies to be truncated at one character if they
${indent}were re-edited.${ulend}

${h3}0.12 - 1998/04/23:${h3end}

New features:${pul}

${bullet}Compatible with MSDOS. All source code files have been changed to
${indent}single-case, 8.3 form, and #ifdef's are used on filenames internally where
${indent}necessary. (Most other issues are taken care of by DJGPP, though some
${indent}Makefile changes were necessary, and the starting directory is now
${indent}restored on termination -- needed in DOS, but not in Unix.)

${bullet}Compatible with PDCurses (as distributed with DJGPP), and SysV curses
${indent}(specifically, Solaris). Note that the shadows on windows are opaque if
${indent}you compile with SysV curses. (I also added \"#define USE_SHADOWS\", which
${indent}you can comment out or remove to get rid of the shadows
${indent}altogether.)${ulend}

Bug fixes and such:${pul}

${bullet}After the reorganization of resource.C in version 0.11 (if not before),
${indent}any change to the value of mmHomeDir in .mmailrc would leave the
${indent}bwPacketDir, bwReplyDir, etc. variables unaffacted.

${bullet}memError() now works correctly, even before initialization of the
${indent}interface. Fatal errors in general will be reported better in this
${indent}version.

${bullet}Some additonal bounds checking on sprintf() calls.

${bullet}tmpnam() checked. In principle, as few as 26 temporary filenames might be
${indent}available from it (which should still be enough, unless you write a whole
${indent}lot of replies).${ulend}

${h3}0.11 - 1998/03/21:${h3end}

New features:${pul}

${bullet}Area and system descriptions added to saved messages.

${bullet}I removed the last remaining command-line option, \"-m\", on the grounds
${indent}that it was useless. (This is a new UNfeature.) After testing it on my
${indent}9600 bps terminal, it doesn't appear to improve the speed; and the
${indent}alternate color scheme, which it was originally designed to select, was
${indent}never implemented. (Instead, I've added inversing to the top and bottom
${indent}bars in the letter window, and made a few other changes to make it more
${indent}monochrome-friendly.)${ulend}

Bug fixes and such:${pul}

${bullet}resource.C and resource.h rewritten and simplified to allow compilation
${indent}with gcc 2.8.1. (It's not yet clear to me why the old version didn't work,
${indent}but this is better anyway.) There are still a few warnings, but it works
${indent}OK.

${bullet}When entering the From:, To:, and Subject: on replies, the full width of
${indent}the fields had not been available. Under some circumstances, this could
${indent}even cause a segfault. These lengths still need to be checked more
${indent}stringently.

${bullet}Automatic \"Re:\" adding now takes place before subject-line editing,
${indent}instead of after. This allows users to see that it will be added, and to
${indent}override it if desired. (It also saves a few bytes of code!) I don't know
${indent}why I did it the other way before.

${bullet}In the event of a \"Fatal Error:\" exit, MultiMail will now clean up after
${indent}itself, as with normal exits. Also, failed memory allocation is now
${indent}explicitly checked.

${bullet}Default paths for \"zip\" and \"unzip\" removed. (These would only show up
${indent}if the paths were not defined in the .mmailrc -- as they are with the
${indent}default .mmailrc.) Thanks to Carey Bloodworth for pointing this out.

${bullet}If the message numbers exceeded 5 digits (i.e., 100000+), they would mess
${indent}up the display in the letter list. Now, it takes 6. :-)

${bullet}Much internal reorganization.

${bullet}Fixed a bug with my website -- the new-style URL (/~wmcbrine/) messed up
${indent}some relative pathnames. :-)${ulend}

${h3}0.10 - 1998/03/07:${h3end}

New features:${pul}

${bullet}Shadowed windows! Tell me if you like them.

${bullet}SIGWINCH support. You can now resize the terminal (e.g., maximize the
${indent}xterm) while MultiMail is running, and it will adapt to the new
${indent}size.${ulend}

Bug fixes and such:${pul}

${bullet}Under Solaris, the help menu area was not being cleared when changing from
${indent}one menu to another.

${bullet}One more space available in letter list (now consistent with the other
${indent}lists).

${bullet}On some systems (such as Linux w/ glibc, and NetBSD), if you attempted to
${indent}read a packet that didn't already have a \"bbsid.red\" file (mm's read
${indent}markers) in it, MultiMail v0.9 would segfault right after unzipping a
${indent}packet, due to a very stupid attempt to call fclose() with a NULL pointer.
${indent}Under Linux w/ libc.5, this actually worked OK; and I didn't notice it on
${indent}my NetBSD test system because the packets there already had .red files in
${indent}them. Thanks again to Cesar Cardoso for reporting the problem.${par}

${indent}Due to the seriousness of this bug, I'm releasing v0.10 early.${ulend}

${h3}0.9 - 1998/02/26:${h3end}

New features:${pul}

${bullet}Added alias, \"!\", for F2. Added Tab as an alias for right arrow (next
${indent}unread) in letter list.

${bullet}Better handling of screen widths other than 80; better use of available
${indent}screen space even in 80 columns. Still to do: handle SIGWINCH.

${bullet}QWK now has the option (on by default) to show only those areas which have
${indent}messages in them, instead of the full area list. I set this on by default
${indent}to match the behavior of the Blue Wave side; you can change this in the
${indent}top-level Makefile. Currently, it's only a compile-time option. (In the
${indent}future, I'll add the ability to do a full list in Blue Wave mode, and to
${indent}toggle the mode at runtime.)

${bullet}.REP and .NEW filenames are now forced to lowercase. Should be easier to
${indent}type. :-) But if you have any uppercase-named reply packets from previous
${indent}versions, you'll have to manually rename them before 0.9 will recognize
${indent}them. Sorry.

${bullet}Blue Wave mode now works on big-endian systems! The full functionality of
${indent}MultiMail is now available on all platforms where it compiles. And
${indent}\"-fpack-struct\" is no longer needed in the Makefile -- which I hope may
${indent}mean increased portability.

${bullet}system() calls to rm and sed have been eliminated.${ulend}

Bug fixes and such:${pul}

${bullet}Strip spaces from Blue Wave subject lines; fixes sorting in some cases.

${bullet}In Blue Wave mode, MultiMail was using LF as a paragraph delimiter. The
${indent}correct behavior is to use CR as the delimiter and ignore any LFs. Thanks
${indent}to Marc D. Williams for submitting a packet that required this fix.

${bullet}Messages in Blue Wave packets are supposed to have a leading space, but
${indent}packets produced by the ReneWave door lacked them. They also contained
${indent}nulls in messages (a no-no). MultiMail now deals with these problems
${indent}without flaking out. Thanks again to M.D.W.

${bullet}With Blue Wave packets, MultiMail now scans for \"*.inf\", instead of
${indent}assuming that the packet name minus the extension is the basename.
${indent}Normally, that is the case, but the \"welcome!.000\" packet that comes
${indent}with the Blue Wave reader -- which uses \"welcome\" internally -- is a
${indent}counterexample. MultiMail can now read this packet. :-)

${bullet}Startup for QWK packets is much faster, especially on slow systems.
${indent}Previous versions would attempt to open the .ndx file for each area
${indent}defined in the control.dat (and would do so several times for each area),
${indent}whether it existed or not; 0.9 scans to see which .ndx files actually
${indent}exist first.

${bullet}Changed ANSI viewer to work better with certain messages. Really, I should
${indent}make it user-definable, instead of being hard-wired to \"less\"; but I'm
${indent}probably going to make it into an internal function anyway.

${bullet}Added \"#include ${lt}sys/types.h${gt}\" to mmail/mmail.h. Usually I wouldn't
${indent}mention a change of this type, but in this case, it was done to get
${indent}MultiMail to compile with glibc (libc 6). Thanks to Cesar Cardoso for
${indent}reporting the problem and testing the solution.

${bullet}Saved messages are now wrapped at 80 columns, regardless of screen width
${indent}at the time of saving; and the date is now added to the saved header.

${bullet}Replying to a message no longer messes up the right margin of the original
${indent}when viewing it immediately after replying.

${bullet}Paths are no longer stored with the .red file when using LHA. In previous
${indent}versions, this could cause the storing of multiple .red files into a
${indent}packet.

${bullet}Next/previous unread in letter list now work correctly, even with messages
${indent}that have manually been marked Unread.

${bullet}Miscellaneous minor internal fixes and optimizations.${ulend}

${h3}0.8 - 1998/02/10:${h3end}

New features:${pul}

${bullet}\"Re: \" is stripped from subject lines, for sorting and display purposes,
${indent}and added automatically on replies (unless doing so would truncate the
${indent}subject). Subject sorting is now case-insensitive.

${bullet}Letter window now displays \"bbsnum (x of y)\", for consistency with the
${indent}letter list and to provide more information.

${bullet}Slightly expanded the area description length to make better use of the
${indent}available space. Also, in the letter list, more of the subject is shown.

${bullet}Restored the \"line/lines\" counter found in early versions of MultiMail.
${indent}This shows the length of the message in lines, and the number of the top
${indent}line on screen.

${bullet}Temporary files are now cleared at the end of a session. Also, since
${indent}MultiMail now generates a unique temporary directory for each session, a
${indent}single user can run multiple concurrent sessions. (Just don't try to read
${indent}the same packet in each one!)

${bullet}System uname added to Blue Wave tearline (if it will fit).

${bullet}Character set translation can now be toggled at runtime, by pressing 'c',
${indent}instead of at compilation time.

${bullet}Packet type is now recognized automatically, based on the filename's
${indent}extension. (You can still force the other type.) Consequently, the \"-b\"
${indent}and \"-q\" options have been removed.

${bullet}The Blue Wave area list now uses the description instead of the echotag.
${indent}This is much more useful, and conforms to the Blue Wave reader.

${bullet}The number of the original message is now passed to the door for reply
${indent}linking.

${bullet}In the letter window, the top and bottom bars are now inversed when in
${indent}monochrome. In the various lists, the highlight bar is now drawn with
${indent}stdout(), for greater contrast.

${bullet}Many changes to the top-level Makefile; it's now more portable, and
${indent}commented. You can now set the location of the ncurses header file here,
${indent}instead of editing the source.

${bullet}The packet list is now sorted, and shows file sizes as well as dates.

${bullet}The backquote character (\`) is converted to an ESC when using the ANSI
${indent}viewer. (Some systems recode ESC characters this way.)

${bullet}You can now Kill packets from the packet list.${ulend}

Bug fixes and such:${pul}

${bullet}If all preexisting replies were deleted, attempting to create a new reply
${indent}during the same session could cause a segfault.

${bullet}Terminal newlines stripped from replies. Conforms to the Blue Wave reader;
${indent}supresses gaps after the tagline with some doors.

${bullet}QWK subject fields had been truncated at 24 characters. (The field is 25
${indent}chars.)

${bullet}The tagline file can now be hand-edited without introducing blank lines.

${bullet}In the letter window, PgDn, End, and the down arrow now stop at the actual
${indent}end of the text.

${bullet}No more extra junk in Blue Wave reply packets.

${bullet}Blue Wave replies can now be safely reedited. (Previously, the line
${indent}endings could be messed up -- left in Unix format.) Stray characters no
${indent}longer appear at the end of Blue Wave replies while viewing them.

${bullet}Blue Wave mode, like QWK mode, now shows the BBS message numbers in the
${indent}letter list, instead of the messages' position in the packet.

${bullet}Trailing \", Sysop\" stripped from sysop name in QWK mode.

${bullet}Opening reply packets that were generated by the Blue Wave reader caused a
${indent}segfault, due to case mismatch; it now works correctly.

${bullet}Version number \"encryption\" for Blue Wave replies fixed (so the number
${indent}appears correctly in tearlines). (IMO, the Blue Wave specs are in error in
${indent}describing this feature -- bluewave.h refers to addition when it should
${indent}say subtraction.)

${bullet}Left and right arrow keys in the area list now work much faster when
${indent}skipping empty areas, and can take you to the first and last areas,
${indent}instead of second and next-to-last.

${bullet}Killed the stupid repeating-REPLY-area bug in Blue Wave mode.

${bullet}When creating Blue Wave replies, MultiMail now makes the proper choice
${indent}between \"real name\" and \"alias\", depending on the area flags.${ulend}

${h3}0.7 - 1997/12/07:${h3end}

New features:${pul}

${bullet}Right and left arrow keys now select next/previous unread message in an
${indent}area, similarly to the way they function in the area list (jumping to
${indent}non-empty areas).

${bullet}ANSI viewer. Hit ^A while reading a message to view it in color, if it has
${indent}ANSI codes embedded. This is still rudimentary; it uses \"less\" as the
${indent}viewer, and it depends on the terminal to interpret the codes.

${bullet}Private flag support. Complete, except for Blue Wave area flag checks.

${bullet}Character set translation is essentially complete. The only further
${indent}changes I envision are the ability to turn translation on or off at run
${indent}time, instead of at compile time; some possible changes to the translation
${indent}table; and maybe additional character sets.

${bullet}Stolen taglines are checked for dupes, included only once.

${bullet}With some minor changes, I got it to work under SunOS (Solaris). No longer
${indent}just a Linux program! :-) So, the tearline is now derived from the uname.
${indent}Blue Wave mode still requires a little-endian system.

${bullet}QWK \"Personal\" conference.

${bullet}Many key aliases added, mainly for use on terminals that don't support
${indent}keys like PgDn and F1. Also, Space Bar now functions as a combination
${indent}PgDn/Enter in the letter window, to allow paging through a conference.

${bullet}Marking and read/unread toggle now work from the letter list, simplifying
${indent}bulk marking. In the REPLY area, Kill now works from the letter list.

${bullet}Automatic creation of .mmailrc and the mmail directories; no more \"make
${indent}install_dirs\".

${bullet}Changed bluewave.h to version 3. (No related feature changes yet.) I now
${indent}use it in unmodified form; \"-fpack-struct\" is sufficient.${ulend}

Bug fixes and such:${pul}

${bullet}Suppression of \"hidden\" text lines added for Blue Wave (already present
${indent}for QWK).

${bullet}Append saved files instead of overwrite.

${bullet}If saving without a path specified, save in the \"save\" directory.

${bullet}Better adaptation to nonstandard screen sizes.

${bullet}Really random taglines (previously, there was no call to srand).

${bullet}\"Save lastread pointers?\" and \"Reply area has changed...\" messages now
${indent}come up only when appropriate.

${bullet}\"Personal\" column in area list removed in QWK mode. Maybe not a bug, but
${indent}it was unused.

${bullet}Fall back to login name if no alias name defined. (It was using only the
${indent}alias name, sometimes leading to blank From: lines in Blue Wave mode. This
${indent}feature needs more work -- the alias should not always be the default.)

${bullet}Various date fixes (QWK and Blue Wave).

${bullet}Print the right area type for QWK Replies.

${bullet}Area names padded out with spaces when necessary to correct a cosmetic
${indent}defect in the REPLIES/PERSONAL letter lists' \"Area\" fields.

${bullet}Version number references made consistent.

${bullet}Remove extra bytes from ends of messages (QWK and Blue Wave).

${bullet}A big one: Kill the *correct* reply messages with 'K'. (!)

${bullet}A BIG one: QWK reply area numbers fixed. It was using the internal area
${indent}number, rather than the QWK number; so replies would go to the wrong
${indent}areas! (Under specific conditions -- a packet with conferences that were
${indent}numbered serially, starting from zero -- this would actually work right,
${indent}which is doubtless how the bug snuck in to begin with.)

${bullet}Stop truncating replies. (This bug complimented the extra byte bug,
${indent}preventing segfaults in the old version.)

${bullet}I changed the default directories from \"bwdown\", etc., to \"down\", etc.
${indent}This wasn't a bug, but it was too Blue Wave-centric for a dual-function
${indent}reader. (I believe the original intent of K.T. & T.I. was that the QWK
${indent}implementation would have its own directories, e.g., \"qwkdown\";  but as
${indent}implemented by J.Z., a common directory was used. I may revert to the
${indent}putative original design at some point. Internally, the \"bw\"  prefix is
${indent}still used on many shared structures.)

${bullet}Make .REP packets from the BBSID, not the base packetname.

${bullet}\"Unread\" now counts all messages marked unread, not just those which are
${indent}also unmarked and unreplied.

${bullet}Letter sort fixed (now sorts by number within each subject), and faster.

${bullet}Eliminated the defaulting to \"reply\" when an otherwise undefined key was
${indent}pressed.

${bullet}Calls to todos replaced with internal code.

${bullet}QWK .ndx parser replaced with faster, non-endian-dependent version.

${bullet}Many ncurses changes. Most importantly, shells and (normal) exits now
${indent}restore the screen mode. (Error exits still need fixing.)

${bullet}Makefile changes (including centralizing options in top-level Makefile).
${indent}Could do with a bit more changing, I think.

${bullet}A big one (since it prevented me from even using 0.6, as it was): Fixed
${indent}segfaults on opening packets with uppercase names within (i.e., those from
${indent}most or all DOS-based BBSes).

${bullet}Many minor changes to suppress warning messages during compilation.

${bullet}Many, many more. :-) These are just the user-visible ones.${ulend}

Bugs unfixed:${pul}

${bullet}The lockup-on-exit bug, described below as having appeared in 0.3 and
${indent}disappeared in 0.4, has resurfaced. I too am unable to trace it. It can
${indent}come or go after almost any random change in the code.${ulend}

